## IDEAS AND VOICES FROM THE FIELD — HOW THE FOUR SCHOOLS ENACT THESE PEDAGOGIES

### A. School-Wide Structures and Practices

DAILY AND ONGOING ACTIVITIES:
- Morning/Afternoon Prayer by Grade Level with PBIS Expectations (Mater Dei)
- Daily SEL (Social Emotional Learning) every morning (Mater Dei): Monday reflects on the previous day's gospel and how to implement Catholic teachings into daily life
- Student Support Team (Mater Dei): school counselor, student support coordinator, and assistant principal working in conjunction for behavioral, academic, and social-emotional support
- Student Advocacy Team (Archbishop Borders): principal, AP, social worker, counselor, nurse, and academic interventionist approach student needs with support and care
- Responsive Classroom practices daily (Risen Christ): evidence-based practices for safe, engaging school communities; starts from the premise that social-emotional skills, character building, and academic achievement are intertwined
- Mass Buddies (Risen Christ, also St. Kevin): older classes paired with younger classes to sit together at Mass; older students guide younger students in respectful participation
- Golden Paws (used at Risen Christ): when the whole class shows responsibility, orderliness, attentiveness, or respect, the class receives a Golden Paw — goal is ten golden paws within a month

MONTHLY ACTIVITIES:
- Spirit Families (Risen Christ): multi-grade groups meeting monthly to explore faith and character, fostering community and interconnectedness among all grades
- Buddies (Mater Dei): middle school students partnered with K-2 students; go to mass together and meet throughout the year
- Virtue Awards (Mater Dei): at the last mass of the month, a student in each grade level is recognized for modeling the virtue of the month
- Virtue of the Month (Archbishop Borders): each month focuses on one virtue — honesty, community-building, generosity, compassion; assembly kicks it off interactively; teachers tailor interdisciplinary lessons to the virtue. Added a Saint of the Month who embodied the virtue

SEASONAL AND SPECIAL ACTIVITIES:
- Garden (Risen Christ): students plant and tend a small garden growing pumpkins, tomatoes, and cucumbers for the community; students eat the harvest
- Garden (Archbishop Borders)
- Gratitude plaques for benefactors
- End-of-Year Awards (Mater Dei): Academic Excellence, Juan Diego Award (perseverance and hard work), Crusader Award (a student who embodies all virtues), excellence in enrichment
- AAA Safety Patrol member of the month/trimester

LITURGY:
- Mass: Students attend weekly mass at local parish. Students practice virtues of community awareness, leadership, service, and respect through participation.

AWARDS, CAMPAIGNS, AND DISPLAYS:
- "Cada Encuentro / Every Encounter" (Risen Christ annual theme): emphasizing active engagement with other people who embody the divine — not merely being in the presence of a moral exemplar
- "Con gran amor / With great love" (Risen Christ theme, from St. Teresa of Calcutta: "We can do no great things, only small things with great love"): reminding the community that everything we do reflects our character, no matter how small the action
- School mural at student entrance (Risen Christ)
- "El Gozo del Señor es mi Fortaleza / The Joy of the Lord is my Strength"
- Student Learning Expectations (Mater Dei): displayed in every classroom
- Nicolette Finley Award (Risen Christ eighth grade): "In recognition of strong academic ability, strength of character, and leadership skills following the model of Jesus Christ"

BEHAVIORAL PLANS:
- PBIS at Archbishop Borders — R.O.A.R: Respect, Orderly & Safe, Attend Every Day, Responsibility. Through positive reinforcement, direct instruction, and modeling, students are reminded daily of school expectations
- ClassDojo (Archbishop Borders): awards positive behavior points and communicates with families about student progress
- Golden Dust Pan (Archbishop Borders): awarded to the cleanest classroom — teaching order and responsibility; all students play a role in keeping the classroom safe
- Crusader Tickets (Mater Dei): students recognized by faculty/staff for modeling expectations (Respect, Responsibility, Kindness, Problem Solving); weekly drawing for a prize
- Responsive Classroom (Risen Christ): building relationships, community agreements, and logical consequences create safe, productive learning environments

### B. Classroom Structures and Activities

Every classroom should reflect the four sociocultural competence goals. When students have a sense of belonging and acceptance, they feel emotionally supported. Comfortable sharing and learning builds relationships that promote engagement and a positive learning environment. Students comfortable with teachers will not be afraid to ask for help, more time, or report problems with peers.

CLASSROOM PRACTICES:
- Morning Talk / Morning Writing and Reflections: students need time for conversation; teachers read short stories on character building, problems and solutions, or Bible stories on virtues as a starting point
- Ecosystems + Diversity lesson (example from practice): teaching a unit on ecosystems can include a lesson on Ecosystem Diversity, where diverse living and nonliving things interact in symbiosis — the teacher makes an explicit connection to classroom/community diversity and interpersonal collaboration
- At Risen Christ, significant student disagreements are handled by a team of adults (counselor, director, both English and Spanish teachers) working with students in both languages — finding the most just and meaningful solution
- Classroom helpers/managers as structured responsibility

CORE CONTENT EXAMPLES — MEANINGFUL UNITS AND LESSONS:
- "Kindness from Your Heart" (what we feed ourselves has to come out — we need to feed ourselves with goodness, kind words, kind prayers)
- Snowflakes (St. Kevin's Kindergarten): God made me as unique as a snowflake — students find what makes them special
- Immigration Unit (Risen Christ): immigrant parents invited to share their journey to the US — students learn first-hand about push and pull factors; an Immigration Awards Assembly acknowledges students who have improved in test scores simply for doing better, regardless of grade level
- Good News Spreader (St. Kevin): weekly award presented at school Mass
- Student of the Month (St. Kevin): themed each month — faithful, courage, kindness, generosity, patience
- Golden Tray Lunch Award (Risen Christ): awarded to the most helpful, courteous, and respectful class during lunchtime each week

DUAL LANGUAGE–SPECIFIC CLASSROOM PRACTICES:
- Encouraging peer interpretation at appropriate times among students still developing one of the school's languages
- Availability and accepted use of materials in both languages — even in the "opposite" language classroom (Spanish text in English classroom, etc.)
- Bilingual report cards and classroom newsletters
- Bilingual conference sheets for family communication
- Interpreters at parent conferences even when teachers are bilingual — to level the power dynamic

CLASS / SCHOOL OFFERINGS:
- Social Emotional Learning class, Religion class, integrated into classroom routines
- Pre-K students take turns carrying lunch trash — learning responsibility daily
- Middle schoolers serve as student ambassadors giving school tours — growing in confidence, responsibility, community awareness
- Clubs, sports, after-school activities, and group projects build teamwork
- Archbishop Borders "Breakfast Club" (8th grade): students arrive at 7:30 am, take breakfast baskets to each classroom, collect lunch sheets — learning responsibility, accountability, and modeling service
- Debate in Spanish through Augsburg University and the Minnesota Urban Debate League (Risen Christ)
- Visual Arts, Physical Education, Dance, Technology (digital literacy/citizenship), Theater, Athletics — enrichment that educates the whole child and honors multiple intelligences

### C. Enactment by Adults

Strong, committed leadership is essential in embedding character education. Educational leaders must model virtues, speak to and see each child as an individual and child of God. Teaching accountability, establishing a culture of trust and belonging, and taking time to meet with students and families are part of being an effective leader.

EXAMPLES FROM SCHOOLS:
- At Archbishop Borders, administration guides students toward reflective thinking in response to behaviors — meeting students one-on-one or in small groups when upset or needing support. This builds trust, models respect and awareness, and leads to reflection and confidence. (Example: "Ms. Miller teaches me that even though I'm naturally talkative, I have to learn when I can and cannot talk" — a student teaching reflective thinking, accountability, responsibility)
- At Risen Christ, "Sunny Moments" at every faculty meeting: staff share positive actions from classrooms and personal lives
- Risen Christ conducts all faculty and staff meetings in both English and Spanish with contemporaneous interpretation — ensuring all staff can engage. Occasionally presentations are given in Spanish with non-Spanish speakers listening on devices. This is not just a school that teaches two languages — it is a community that lives in two languages.
- Saintly Service Awards (Risen Christ, diocese-wide): a staff member is nominated each month to represent the virtues of a saint. The whole community can nominate any employee who "acts like a Saint." The awarding process asks for concrete examples of saintly virtues, not general impressions.
- Professional Development Workshops: e.g., Risen Christ facilitated a Lenten retreat and Sociocultural Competence workshop for faculty and staff

## THE FOUR FOCAL SCHOOLS

### Mater Dei Juan Diego Academy (Chula Vista, California)
Website: materdeicatholic.org | Colors: navy and gold
Mission character: presents itself as a multicultural family where inspiring and educating the hearts, minds, and souls of students is essential; older students are like older brothers who inspire the younger ones. High academic achievement, multiculturalism, and faith formation are central. Mater Dei expectations: Respect, Responsibility, Kindness, and Problem Solving. Led by Principal Faina Salter and AP Cristina Torres.

### Archbishop Borders School (Baltimore, Maryland)
Website: abbschool.com | Colors: purple and green
Mission character: prepares students to be dynamic members of society through an educational experience informed by diversity, faith, and academic excellence. Character formation is described as "getting ready for the real world, and doing the right thing." Character is emphasized by teaching students to be well-behaved, civic, and respectful of each other's opinions. PBIS acronym: R.O.A.R. Led by AP Kaitlyn Ramos and teacher Ana Gray.

### Saint Kevin Catholic School (Miami, Florida)
Website: saintkevinschool.com | Colors: navy
Mission character: partners with parents to provide rigorous education centered on Catholic faith formation of the whole child — guiding students to become global citizens with the Eucharist as the center of their lives. Students are encouraged to "do the right thing every day." Teachers promote core ethical and performance values to instill good character; encourage moral development and self-motivation; and foster a caring, supportive community. Led by Principal Mayra Constantino and Dual Language Coordinator Grace Rodriguez.

### Risen Christ Catholic School (Minneapolis, Minnesota)
Website: risenchristschool.org | Colors: purple
Mission character: a bilingual, multicultural, and financially accessible school of excellence, educating children in mind, body, and spirit to live and lead in the example of Jesus Christ. "Holistic approach to educating the child — academics, spiritual formation, and character formation." A school where the vast majority of students come from immigrant families from Spanish-speaking countries: "They are immersed in character building just by being here as children of immigrant parents, primarily of low income, who left family and an uncertain future, then risked crossing a national border to look for work in a language not their own. The children learn character in being part of motivated families in a faith-based learning environment." Led by teacher Kevin Dalum and teacher Davina Van Horenbeeck.

